<p>## 4. ABSTRACT / SUMMARY</p>
<p>### Project Title<br>Library Management Software</p>
<p>### Problem Statement<br>The management of library activities in educational institutions is often cumbersome when conducted manually. It leads to issues such as misplaced records, difficulty in tracking book availability, overdue items, and challenges in generating reports.&nbsp;</p>
<p>### Why the Topic Was Chosen<br>With the increasing reliance on digital technologies, automating library management presents a prime opportunity to enhance efficiency, accuracy, and accessibility.</p>
<p>### Objectives<br>- To create a user-friendly interface for managing library resources.<br>- To enable automated processes for book issuance and returns.<br>- To facilitate comprehensive reporting for better resource management.</p>
<p>### Scope<br>The software functions as a comprehensive solution for both library staff and users, allowing for book management, user registrations, fines management, and various reports generation.&nbsp;</p>
<p>### Methodology<br>The project adopts the Waterfall Model of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC), ensuring structured phases from requirement analysis to maintenance.</p>
<p>### Hardware and Software Used<br>- **Frontend**: HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Bootstrap<br>- **Backend**: PHP<br>- **Database**: MySQL<br>- **Server**: XAMPP</p>
<p>### Testing Technologies Used<br>Manual Testing and Black Box Testing were employed to ensure functionality and performance.</p>
<p>### Expected Contribution<br>This project aims to streamline library operations, significantly reducing manual labor and errors, ultimately enhancing user experience and satisfaction.</p>
<p>---</p>
<p>## 5. SYNOPSIS OF THE PROJECT</p>
<p>The Library Management Software project presents a digital solution for the challenges faced in managing a library. It serves various functions including managing users, books, issue and return processes, and reporting. The software caters to both librarians and users by providing a functional and intuitive interface.</p>
<p>---</p>
<p>## 6. OBJECTIVE AND SCOPE OF THE PROJECT</p>
<p>### Objectives<br>- Automate library operations to eliminate manual errors.<br>- Provide a systematic approach to manage books and users.<br>- Generate real-time reports for better decision-making.</p>
<p>### Scope<br>The software is intended for use in educational and public libraries, providing both front-end access for users and a management interface for librarians.</p>
<p>---</p>
<p>## 7. THEORETICAL BACKGROUND</p>
<p>### Introduction to Library Management Systems<br>Library Management Systems (LMS) are software applications designed to manage library functions such as cataloging, circulation, and inventory management.</p>
<p>### Evolution of Digital Libraries<br>Digital libraries have transitioned traditional libraries into electronic formats, making resources more accessible and easier to manage.</p>
<p>### Benefits of Automation<br>Automation improves efficiency, accuracy, and accessibility while reducing the workload on library staff.</p>
<p>### Existing System<br>Existing systems are often manual, leading to inefficiencies and challenges in maintaining accurate records.</p>
<p>### Proposed System<br>The proposed software automates major library functions, enhancing operational efficiency and user satisfaction.</p>
<p>---</p>
<p>## 8. DEFINITION OF THE PROBLEM</p>
<p>### Issues in Manual Library Management<br>- High risk of data loss and errors.<br>- Time-consuming processes for book issuance and return.<br>- Difficulty in tracking overdue books and fines.</p>
<p>### Need for Computerized Solution<br>A computerized system can streamline operations, provide real-time data, and improve user experience by making information more accessible.</p>
<p>---</p>
<p>## 9. SYSTEM ANALYSIS AND DESIGN</p>
<p>### Requirement Analysis<br>Requirements were gathered from librarians and users to ensure the software meets real-world needs.</p>
<p>### Functional Requirements<br>- User Registration<br>- Book Management<br>- Issue and Return Tracking</p>
<p>### Non-Functional Requirements<br>- Performance<br>- Security<br>- Usability</p>
<p>### Feasibility Study<br>The project&rsquo;s feasibility was assessed in terms of technical, operational, and economic aspects.</p>
<p>### User Requirements<br>The user interface must be intuitive and accessible to users with varying levels of computer literacy.</p>
<p>---</p>
